  "prompt": "How long is a business considered a \"start-up\" for?",
  "response": "There's no universal definition, but generally:\n\n1. Typically 3-5 years is considered the \"start-up\" phase\n\n2. Some key characteristics of a start-up include:\n- Rapid growth potential\n- Innovative business model\n- Seeking external funding\n- Not yet profitable\n- Flexible, dynamic organizational structure\n\n3. Factors that can extend or shorten start-up status:\n- Industry type\n- Funding success\n- Business model\n- Revenue growth\n- Market conditions\n\n4. Venture capitalists and investors often consider a company a start-up until:\n- It becomes profitable\n- Reaches a significant revenue milestone\n- Completes an IPO or major acquisition\n- Stabilizes with consistent growth\n\n5. Some tech companies might be considered start-ups for 7-10 years\n\nThe definition is somewhat flexible and can vary by context, industry, and individual perspective.",
